</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3DBF74D60837FFC4EFD9103D2DB66EEA" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="751A275D0837FFC4EFD9103D2DB66EEA" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1079]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4EFD9103D29026E5A" bold="true" box="[199,308,838,863]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B2A55CDE0837FFC4EC01103C2C056E5A" authority="Becker" authorityName="Becker" box="[799,1075,838,863]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Apotropina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscipleuris">
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4EC01103C2BF26E5A" box="[799,964,839,863]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">A. fuscipleuris</emphasis>
(Becker)
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: proboscis bright brown to yellow; scutum yellowish brown with 
<number id="C36D357A0837FFC4EA2710102D716E86" box="[1337,1351,875,899]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" value="2.0">2</number>
brown longitudinal stripes, which extend to scutoscutellar suture; legs yellow except for mid and hind coxae, distal portions of femora, distal portion of fore tibia and tarsomere 
<number id="C36D357A0837FFC4EC5F10C92B796ECE" box="[833,847,946,971]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" value="5.0">5</number>
yellowish brown. In 
<taxonomicName id="B2A55CDE0837FFC4EB2010C82CD66ECE" box="[1086,1248,947,971]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Apotropina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscipleuris">
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4EB2010C82CD66ECE" box="[1086,1248,947,971]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">A. fuscipleuris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the proboscis is shiny black; the scutum is entirely rusty brown; the legs are reddish yellow except for tarsi black (
<bibRefCitation id="11345AAC0837FFC4EBFE10AD2D456EEA" author="Becker" box="[1248,1395,982,1007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" refString="Becker, T. (1911) Chloropidae. Eine monographische Studie. iii. Die Indo-australische Region. Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici, Budapest, 9, 35 - 170." type="journal article" year="1911">
Becker 
<number id="C36D357A0837FFC4EA2610AC2D456EEA" box="[1336,1395,983,1007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" value="1911.0">1911</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3DBF74D60837FFC4EFD910812A246932" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="751A275D0837FFC4EFD910812A246932" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1079]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4EFD9108129706916" bold="true" box="[199,326,1018,1043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is from the Latin 
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4EC1F10802B166916" box="[769,800,1019,1043]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">bi-</emphasis>
(“two”) and 
<emphasis id="47D1FB4F0837FFC4ECA510802C396917" box="[955,1039,1019,1042]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="126">striatus</emphasis>
(“stripe”), referring to the scutum with 
<number id="C36D357A0837FFC4EFCE176428E86932" box="[208,222,1055,1079]" pageId="4" pageNumber="126" value="2.0">2</number>
brown longitudinal stripes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
